<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO GERALD</font><br>
<tt>Fri May  2  0:32:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gerald, you said it took the vietnam vet 25 to 30 years to get any recognition from the VA, but the Korean vets had to sit it out a hell of a lot longer than we did. Yes, to a certain extent, they have benefitted from the Viet vets &quot;holding the VA feet to the fire&quot;, but you cannot dispute and surely you can empathize, that they came home pretty much they we did, ignored and forgotten, a scourge to the memories of the American public. There cannot be any question that they had suffered a hell of a lot longer, only because they were fewer in numbers and did not have the political pull that vets now enjoy.<br><br>
My uncle was a fighter pilot, was shot down twice, wounded twice, was a POW for three months before he escaped, and then returned to the air. The fighting conditions were different and extreme, and the results is that they also suffered when they came home from PTSD and the like. It wasn't until about 1985, that people remembered that there was a war between the &quot;BIG ONE&quot; and Vietnam.<br><br>
His anger may be displaced, but his gripes are legitimate!
